The bare N-CDs show a bright emission (QY
≈ 15 %
) in the visible range (Fig. 6a). Adding MNPs produces an emission quenching without any spectral shape variations.

To deeply investigate the origin of the quenching, we also studied and compared the decay kinetics of the emission band of N-CDs with or without the MNPs. The kinetics are shown in Fig. 6d. The fluorescence in both cases decays without any spectral changes indicating the presence of a single emitting chromophore. The lifetime (
   τ
) was obtained by fitting the kinetics with a single exponential function. The accuracy of the time constant of the decays is about 0.2 ns.
